<h2 id="comments">Comments</h2>
<CodeBlock Code="@("# Hash-style comment\n// Double-slash comment")" />

<h2 id="settings">Settings block</h2>
<p>The top-level <code>settings</code> block holds your base configuration.</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Settings" />

<h2 id="nested">Nested objects</h2>
<p>A named block becomes a JSON object key. Nest them for hierarchy.</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Nested" />

<h2 id="maps">Named maps</h2>
<p>Because each named block is a key, you build a map of named objects by nesting named blocks:</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Maps" />

<h2 id="arrays">Arrays</h2>
<p>Comma-separated values — commas are optional, a newline also separates items.</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Arrays" />

<h2 id="objects">Object literals in arrays</h2>
<p>
    Prefix each object in an array with a <strong>tag</strong> — any identifier followed by a block.
    The tag is a required syntactic label and is <em>not</em> emitted in the JSON. A bare
    <code>{ … }</code> without a tag is not valid.
</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Objects" />
<p>The same form works as a plain value: <code>Database = connection { Host = "localhost" }</code> produces <code>"Database": { "Host": "localhost" }</code> (the <code>connection</code> tag is discarded).</p>

<h2 id="dotpath">Dot-path assignments</h2>
<CodeBlock Code="@DotPath" />

<h2 id="env">Environment overlays</h2>
<p>
    Each <code>env</code> block takes a <strong>quoted</strong> name and contains an inner
    <code>settings</code> block. It generates a matching <code>appsettings.{Name}.json</code> merged
    onto the base.
</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Env" />

<h2 id="merging">Merging behaviour</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Objects</strong> merge deeply (properties combined).</li>
    <li><strong>Arrays</strong> are replaced entirely (no element merge).</li>
    <li><strong>Primitives</strong> are replaced.</li>
</ul>
<CodeBlock Code="@Merging" />

<h2 id="includes">File includes</h2>
<p>
    Split configuration across files with <code>include</code>. An included file can contribute
    <code>let</code> variables, <code>settings</code> blocks and <code>env</code> blocks — all
    deep-merged in document order, so the including file wins on conflicts.
</p>
<CodeBlock Title="common.settex" Code="@IncludeCommon" />
<CodeBlock Title="appsettings.settex" Code="@IncludeMain" />
<div class="callout callout-note">
    A <code>let</code> variable may only be defined once per scope — avoid redefining the same global
    variable in both an included file and the including file.
</div>

<h2 id="let">Variables with <code>let</code></h2>
<CodeBlock Code="@Let" />
<p>
    Scoping: file-level <code>let</code> is global; a <code>let</code> inside an <code>env</code> block
    shadows the global for that environment; a loop iterator only exists in the loop body.
</p>

<h2 id="expressions">Expressions</h2>
<CodeBlock Code="@Expressions" />
<p><strong>Operators:</strong> arithmetic <code>+ - * /</code>, comparison <code>== != &lt; &lt;= &gt; &gt;=</code>, logical <code>and or not</code>, null-coalescing <code>??</code>. Parentheses group sub-expressions, and <code>+</code> concatenates when either side is a string (coercing numbers and booleans).</p>

<h2 id="interpolation">String interpolation</h2>
<CodeBlock Code="@Interpolation" />
<div class="callout callout-warn">
    <code>${…}</code> is resolved <strong>at compile time</strong> from Settex variables and expressions —
    it is not a placeholder for runtime environment variables. Inject secrets at deployment time through
    .NET's environment-variable or user-secrets providers instead.
</div>

<h2 id="conditionals">Conditional assignments</h2>
<p>Assign a value only when a boolean condition holds. Write the fallback first, the conditional override after.</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@Conditionals" />

<h2 id="setifmissing">Set-if-missing (<code>:=</code>)</h2>
<p>Sets a value only if the path is not already defined — including checking the base settings from within an overlay. Great for defaults.</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@SetIfMissing" />

<h2 id="for">For loops</h2>
<p>Generate array elements dynamically. Each iteration produces exactly one tagged object.</p>
<CodeBlock Code="@ForLoops" />

<h2 id="types">Value types</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Strings</strong> — <code>"double quotes only"</code></li>
    <li><strong>Numbers</strong> — <code>42</code>, <code>3.14</code>, <code>-10</code></li>
    <li><strong>Booleans</strong> — <code>true</code>, <code>false</code></li>
    <li><strong>Null</strong> — <code>null</code></li>
    <li><strong>Arrays</strong> — <code>[1, 2, 3]</code> or multiline</li>
    <li><strong>Objects</strong> — nested blocks, or tagged object literals (<code>tag { … }</code>)</li>
</ul>

